            "answer_text": "Not necessarily. Superhero films are a subgenre of action films. Most superhero films are in the action and adventure genres. But depending on how every superhero got his/her superpowers, superhero films can be either sci-fi or fantasy, or even both. Or further, none of them. However, we must not forget that sci-fi refers to a speculative genre. It doesn\u2019t just refer to one or two scenes or just some tech. Sci-Fi is a genre invested more in the possibilities, discoveries, inventions, impacts of science and concepts like space travel etc. So I don\u2019t think just using science fiction elements actually make these superhero films into science fiction for real unless it\u2019s a major component of them. While fantasy films are normally invested in characters with powers that don\u2019t really need a scientific explanation. Here lies the difference. SF is more inclined towards the world. Fantasy is more inclined towards characters with extraordinary characters. But\u2026 Superhero films fit the best in the definition of action films. Action films feature action sequences, with characters often into physical challenges, especially (not necessarily) pitted against villains they have to fight and overcome the obstacles set by them. Almost every superhero has to fight a villain and his army, something which happens in action films. Just like Batman, for example, fights criminals using his combat skills, John McClane fights the criminals in a similar way with the intention of saving the day too (the only thing is, he kills them). ",
